{"title_page": "David Menzies", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = David Menzies\n| image = \n| fullname = David Menzies\n| birth_date  = \n| birth_place = [[Kirkcaldy]], Scotland\n| death_date  = October 1936\n| height = \n| position = \n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = \n| clubs1 = [[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]]\n| caps1 = \n| goals1 = \n| manageryears1 = 1916\u20131921 \n| manageryears2 = 1921\u20131926 \n| manageryears3 = 1927\u20131936 \n| manageryears4 = 1936\n| managerclubs1 = [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] \n| managerclubs2 = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] \n| managerclubs3 = [[Doncaster Rovers F.C.|Doncaster Rovers]] \n| managerclubs4 = [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]]\n}}\n'''David Menzies''' was a Scottish [[association football|football]] player and [[coach (sport)|manager]].\n\n==Career==\nMenzies was a player at [[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]] where his father was chairman. In 1903 he joined newly formed English side [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] as a reserve player. He also served as a steward and trainer until the outbreak of [[World War I|World War One]]. In July 1916 he began his managerial career at [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] following two years as trainer at the club. He served for two seasons in post-war football leading the club to a mid-table position in [[Football League Second Division|Division Two]].\n\nIn July 1921 he returned to Bradford City to take over from [[Peter O'Rourke]]. O'Rourke had helped City to lift the [[FA Cup Final 1911|FA Cup]] and kept City in [[Football League First Division|Division One]] for nine successive seasons giving Menzies a difficult task to follow. City were relegated in Menzies' first season. For four more seasons the club struggled in the bottom half of Division Two and Menzies resigned in June 1926.\n\nA year later he became secretary-manager of [[Doncaster Rovers F.C.|Doncaster Rovers]]. He helped lead them to the [[Football League Third Division North|Division Three (North)]] title in [[1934\u201335 in English football|1934\u201335]]. The following season, he resigned to rejoin Hull City. Hull were relegated in [[1935\u201336 in English football|1935\u201336]] from Division Two.\n\nMenzies died in office in October 1936.\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Manager===\n* '''[[Football League Third Division North]]:'''\n**'''Winner (1):''' [[1934-35 in English football|1934\u201335]] (''[[Doncaster Rovers F.C.|Doncaster Rovers]]'')\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book\n| last = Frost\n| first = Terry\n| title = Bradford City A Complete Record 1903\u20131988\n| publisher = Breedon Books Sport\n| year = 1988\n| pages = 66\n| isbn = 0-907969-38-0}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{soccerbase (manager)|349|David Menzies}}\n\n{{Hull City A.F.C. managers}}\n{{Bradford City A.F.C. managers}}\n{{Doncaster Rovers F.C. managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Menzies, David}}\n[[Category:1936 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Hull City A.F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Bradford City A.F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Doncaster Rovers F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Scottish football managers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Association footballers not categorized by position]]\n\n\n{{Scotland-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = David Menzies\n| image = \n| fullname = David Menzies\n| birth_date  = \n| birth_place = [[Kirkcaldy]], Scotland\n| death_date  = October 1936\n| height = \n| position = \n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = \n| clubs1 = [[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]]\n| caps1 = \n| goals1 = \n| manageryears1 = 1916\u20131921 \n| manageryears2 = 1921\u20131926 \n| manageryears3 = 1927\u20131936 \n| manageryears4 = 1936\n| managerclubs1 = [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] \n| managerclubs2 = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] \n| managerclubs3 = [[Doncaster Rovers F.C.|Doncaster Rovers]] \n| managerclubs4 = [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]]\n}}\n'''David Menzies''' was a Scottish [[association football|football]] player and [[coach (sport)|manager]].\n\n==Career==\nMenzies was a player at [[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]] where his father was chairman. In 1903 he joined newly formed English side [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] as a reserve player. He also served as a steward and trainer until the outbreak of [[World War I|World War One]]. In July 1916 he began his managerial career at [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] following two years as trainer at the club. He served for two seasons in post-war football leading the club to a mid-table position in [[Football League Second Division|Division Two]].\n\nIn July 1921 he returned to Bradford City to take over from [[Peter O'Rourke]]. O'Rourke had helped City to lift the [[FA Cup Final 1911|FA Cup]] and kept City in [[Football League First Division|Division One]] for nine successive seasons giving Menzies a difficult task to follow. City were relegated in Menzies' first season. For four more seasons the club struggled in the bottom half of Division Two and Menzies resigned in June 1926.\n\nA year later he became secretary-manager of [[Doncaster Rovers F.C.|Doncaster Rovers]]. He helped lead them to the [[Football League Third Division North|Division Three (North)]] title in [[1934\u201335 in English football|1934\u201335]]. The following season, he resigned to rejoin Hull City. Hull were relegated in [[1935\u201336 in English football|1935\u201336]] from Division Two.\n\nMenzies died in office in October 1936.\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Manager===\n* '''[[Football League Third Division North]]:'''\n**'''Winner (1):''' [[1934-35 in English football|1934\u201335]] (''[[Doncaster Rovers F.C.|Doncaster Rovers]]'')\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book\n| last = Frost\n| first = Terry\n| title = Bradford City A Complete Record 1903\u20131988\n| publisher = Breedon Books Sport\n| year = 1988\n| pages = 66\n| isbn = 0-907969-38-0}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{soccerbase (manager)|349|David Menzies}}\n\n{{Hull City A.F.C. managers}}\n{{Bradford City A.F.C. managers}}\n{{Doncaster Rovers F.C. managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Menzies, David}}\n[[Category:1936 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Hull City A.F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Bradford City A.F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Doncaster Rovers F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Scottish football managers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n\n\n[[Category:Association footballers not categorized by position]]\n{{Scotland-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Menzies"}
{"title_page": "Mitzi McCall", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n|image =\n| name = Mitzi McCall\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1932|9|9}}  \n| birth_place = [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| occupation = Actress\n| years_active = 1955\u2013present\n| spouse = Jack Tolen (div.)<br>[[Charlie Brill]] (1960\u2013present)\n| children = Jenny Brill\n| signature = MitziMcCall.png\n| other_names = Mitzi Steiner\n}}\n'''Mitzi McCall''' (born September 9, 1932) is an American actress.\n\n==Life and career==\n\n=== Television ===\nIn the early 1950s, then known as '''Mitzi Steiner''', McCall had the ''Kiddie Castle'' program on [[KDKA-TV#DuMont origins (1949\u20131954)|WDTV-TV]] in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.<ref name=ppg/> She received national attention in 1952 via an Associated Press story about a five-year-old Pittsburgh girl with a cleft palate who spoke her first words while watching the actress in a pantomime on television. Afterward, doctors \"didn't know what to say. They held a special meeting, examined Claire, and told the happy parents that she was cured.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=TV, a Miracle of Science, Works 'Miracle Cure' on Girl |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23954903/mitzi_steiner/ |work=The Lincoln Star |agency=Associated Press |date=February 10, 1952 |location=Nebraska, Lincoln |page=7-D|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = September 22, 2018}} {{Open access}}</ref> In 1953, she was featured on ''Studio 10'', a program on [[KGTV#History|KFSD-TV]] in San Diego, California.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cohen |first1=Harold V. |title=The Drama Desk |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23966601/mitzi_steiner/ |work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette |date=November 10, 1953 |location=Pennsylvania, Pittsburgh |page=18|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = September 22, 2018}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n\nMcCall also performed in productions at the [[Pittsburgh Playhouse]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fanning |first1=Win |title=Radio and Television in Review |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23955286/mitzi_steiner/ |work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette |date=November 13, 1952 |location=Pennsylvania, Pittsburgh |page=35|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = September 22, 2018}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n\nShe was a performer on ''[[Rowan & Martin's Laugh-In]]''.{{r|etvs|page1=913}} McCall was also a series regular on television series such as ''[[Life Goes On (TV series)|Life Goes On]]'' and  ''[[Silk Stalkings]]'' (where she appeared as the wife of Brill's character),{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}} On animated series, she provided the voice of Auntie Marina in ''[[Snorks]]'',{{r|etvs|page1=986}} the voice of Mother Goose in ''[[Mother Goose and Grimm (TV series)|Mother Goose and Grimm]],''{{r|etvs|page1=718}} the voice of Sylvia Jenkins in ''[[Free for All (TV series)|Free for All]]'',{{r|etvs|page1=365}} and a variety of voices on ''The Paw Paws''.{{r|etvs|page1=819}} She played Miriam Lerner on ''[[Alright Already (TV series)|Alright Already]]''.<ref name=\"etvs\">{{cite book|last1=Terrace|first1=Vincent|title=Encyclopedia of Television Shows, 1925 through 2010|date=2011|publisher=McFarland & Company, Inc., Publishers|location=Jefferson, N.C.|isbn=978-0-7864-6477-7|page=33|edition=2nd}}</ref>\n\nOther credits include guest appearances on ''[[The Twilight Zone (1959 TV series)|The Twilight Zone]]'', ''[[Maude (TV series)|Maude]]'', ''[[Dharma & Greg]]'', ''[[Chuck (TV series)|Chuck]]'', as well as voice over work for many cartoons. In 1971, she was the voice of Penny on ''[[The Flintstones]]'' spin-off ''[[The Pebbles and Bamm-Bamm Show]]''.{{r|etvs|page1=820}} She was a panelist on the game show ''[[Match Game]]'' during its 1970s revival, and appeared with [[Charlie Brill]] on ''[[Tattletales]]''.\n\n=== McCall and Brill ===\nMcCall and Charlie Brill appeared on ''[[The Ed Sullivan Show]]'' on February 9, 1964, the episode that featured the U.S. television debut of [[The Beatles]]. Their act can be seen on the DVD of the Beatles' appearances on the Sullivan show.  They were interviewed in 2005 for the \"Big Break\" episode of [[Public Radio International|PRI]] radio program ''[[This American Life]],'' regarding their Beatles-Sullivan experience, including a dressing room encounter with [[John Lennon]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Human Spectacle 2015|url=http://www.thisamericanlife.org/radio-archives/episode/568/transcript|accessdate=October 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThey were spotted in 1963 while performing together in [[Honolulu]] by the Australian television producer John Collins, who produced ''[[The Tonight Show]]'' for TCN-9 in Sydney. Collins was seeking a replacement for the then unknown Irish comedian [[Dave Allen (comedian)|Dave Allen]], who had hosted the program for the previous two seasons and wanted to return to Ireland. Collins approached them and they agreed but could not start an Australian engagement until their Hawaiian engagement was complete. They recommended an American comedian, their friend [[Don Lane]], who was also working in Hawaii, to fill in during the meantime. Collins agreed to this. Lane started his Australian engagement and was an immediate success. Ratings were sensational and the network was delighted. It was going to be difficult if not impossible to replace him once the Brills became available. When they did, the preference was obvious and their engagement was cancelled after six weeks. Lane resumed their spot and remained successful in Australian television for the ensuing thirty-five years.\n\nIn 1967, McCall and Brill had a comedy recording, ''From Our Point of View'', released by [[ABC Records]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Special Merit Picks: Comedy |url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-Billboard-IDX/IDX/60s/1967/Billboard%201967-04-01-OCR-Page-0036.pdf#search=%22mitzi%20mccall%22 |accessdate=23 September 2018 |work=Billboard |date=April 1, 1967 |page=40}}</ref> Later that year, the duo signed with Congressional Records.<ref>{{cite news |title=Signings |url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-Billboard-IDX/IDX/60s/1967/Billboard%201967-11-04-OCR-Page-0020.pdf#search=%22mitzi%20mccall%22 |accessdate=23 September 2018 |work=Billboard |date=November 4, 1967 |page=20}}</ref>\n\n=== Shawlee and McCall ===\nIn the early 1960s, McCall and actress [[Joan Shawlee]] formed a team to perform as a night club act,<ref name=\"bg\">{{cite news |title=Joan Shawlee Sparkles Like a Spring Tonic |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23940101/joan_shawlee/ |work=The Boston Globe |date=April 30, 1961 |location=Massachusetts, Boston |page=65|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = September 21, 2018}} {{Open access}}</ref> debuting the act at the Club Robaire in Cleveland.<ref>{{cite news |title=They're Back |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23952672/joan_shawlee_mitzi_mccall/ |work=The Los Angeles Times |date=October 20, 1960 |location=California, Los Angeles |page=54|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = September 22, 2018}} {{Open access}}</ref> In January 1961, syndicated newspaper columnist [[Dorothy Kilgallen]] reported that the team was \"causing quite a stir\", and she cited the partners' discrepancy in height \u2014 \"Joan being six feet, three inches tall and Mitzi four feet, 10 inches short.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kilgallen |first1=Dorothy |title=The Voice of Broadway |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23952810/joan_shawlee_mitzi_mccall/ |work=The Mercury |date=January 7, 1961 |location=Pennsylvania, Pottstown |page=4|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = September 22, 2018}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, McCall had a supporting role as Bonnie in the film ''[[World's Greatest Dad]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nIn the early 1950s, McCall was married to Jack Tolen, a television director and production manager.<ref name=\"ppg\">{{cite news |last1=Fanning |first1=Win |title=Radio-Television |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23954040/mitzi_mccall/ |work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette |date=June 29, 1954 |location=Pennsylvania, Pittsburgh |page=25|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = September 22, 2018}} {{Open access}}</ref> She and Charlie Brill met in 1959 and married the following year.<ref>California Marriage Index, 1960-1985.</ref> They have a daughter, L.A.-based yoga instructor Jenny Brill.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Films===\n{{div col|colwidth=26em}}\n* ''[[You're Never Too Young]]'' - Skeets Powell (1955)\n* ''[[Machine-Gun Kelly (film)|Machine-Gun Kelly]]'' - Harriet (uncredited) (1958)\n* ''[[War of the Satellites]]'' - Mitzi (1958)\n* ''[[The Cry Baby Killer]]'' - Evelyn (1958)\n* ''[[Deep Blood]]'' - Ben's Mother (1989)\n* ''[[White Palace (film)|White Palace]]'' - Sophie Rosen (1990)\n* ''[[The Opposite Sex and How to Live with Them]]'' - Freida Crown (1992)\n* ''[[EDtv]]'' - Fig Lady (1999)\n* ''Hard Four'' - Myrna Segal (2007)\n* ''[[World's Greatest Dad]]'' - Bonnie (2009)\n* ''[[Crimson Peak]]'' - Additional voices (2015)\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Television series===\n{{div col|colwidth=26em}}\n* ''[[Rowan & Martin's Laugh-In]]'' - \"herself\" in \"The Fun Couple\" sketches (1968-1969)\n* ''[[Maude (TV series)|Maude]]'' - Estelle Ellinger (Episode: \"Nostalgia Party\") (1974)\n* ''[[Family (1976 TV series)|Family]]'' - Sally (Episode: \"Princess in the Tower\") (1978)\n* ''[[Life Goes On (TV series)|Life Goes On]]'' - Midge (1991-1992)\n* ''[[Silk Stalkings]]'' - Fran Lipschitz (1993-1999)\n* ''[[Seinfeld]]'' - Donna (Episode: \"The Secretary\") (1994)\n* ''[[Ellen (TV series)|Ellen]]'' - Rochelle Shapiro (Episode: \"Too Hip for the Room\") (1996)\n* ''[[Alright Already (TV series)|Alright Already]]'' - Miriam Lerner (1997-1998)\n* ''[[Caroline in the City]]'' - Lois (Episode: \"Caroline and the Little White Lies\") (1998)\n* ''[[Becker]]'' - Mrs. Gould (Episode: \"Hate Thy Neighbor\") (1999)\n* ''[[Dharma & Greg]]'' - Florence (Episode: \"With a Little Help from My Friend\") (2001)\n* ''[[The Suite Life of Zack and Cody]]'' - Doreen (Episode \"Club Twin\") (2007)\n* ''[[Hannah Montana]]'' - Woman (Episode: \"My Best Friend's Boyfriend\") (2007)\n* ''[[Chuck (TV series)|Chuck]]'' - Blanche (Episode: \"Chuck Versus the Broken Heart\") (2009)\n{{div col end}}\n\n====Animation====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"white-space:nowrap\"\n|-\n!  Year !! Title !!Role!!Notes\n|- \n|1971||''[[The Pebbles and Bamm-Bamm Show]]''|| Penny Pillar||16 Episodes\n|- \n|1972-1974||''[[The Flintstone Comedy Hour]]''|| Penny Pillar||13 Episodes\n|- \n|1977-1978||''[[Fred Flintstone and Friends]]''|| Penny Pillar||\n|- \n|1980-1981||''[[The Fonz and the Happy Days Gang]]''|| Additional Voices||\n|- \n|1982-1983||''[[The Scooby & Scrappy-Doo/Puppy Hour]]''|| Additional Voices||\n|- \n|1983||''[[Lucky Luke]]''|| Ma Dalton||\n|- \n|1984||''[[The New Scooby-Doo Mysteries]]''|| Additional Voices||\n|- \n|1984-1985||''[[Snorks]]''|| Auntie Marina||7 Episodes\n|- \n|1985-1986||''[[Paw Paws]]''|| Additional Voices||\n|- \n|1990||''[[Gravedale High]]''|| Additional Voices||\n|- \n|1991||''[[Talespin]]''|| Una||Episode: \"Destiny Rides Again\"\n|- \n|1991||''[[Yo Yogi!]]''|| Talula LaTrane||8 Episodes\n|- \n|1991||''[[Darkwing Duck]]''|| Ammonia Pine||3 Episodes\n|-\n|1991-1992||''[[Mother Goose and Grimm (TV series)|Mother Goose and Grimm]]''|| Mother Goose||7 Episodes\n|-\n|1994||''[[Duckman]]''|| Additional voices ||Episode: \"Psyche\"\n|-\n|1995||''[[Captain Planet and the Planeteers]]''|| Mame Slaughter||Episode: \"Five Ring Panda-Monium\"\n|-\n|1997||''[[Cow and Chicken]]''|| Receptionist||Episode: \"Part Time Job\"\n|- \n|1997||''[[AAAHH!!! Real Monsters]]''|| Custodian Monster||1 Episode\n|-\n|1998||''[[Hey Arnold!]]''|| Pearl ||Episode: \"Arnold's Thanksgiving\"\n|-\n|1999||''[[Histeria!]]''|| [[Golda Meir]]||Episode: \"Histeria Around the World 2\"\n|- \n|2000||''[[The Wild Thornberrys]]''|| Vulture||Episode: \"Gift of Gab\"\n|- \n|2002||''[[Ice Age (2002 film)|Ice Age]]''|| Glyptodont||Film Role\n|- \n|2003||''[[Free for All (TV series)|Free for All]]''|| Sylvia Jenkins||7 Episodes\n|- \n|2006||''[[The Grim Adventures of Billy and Mandy]]''|| Nanny||Episode: \"Scary Poppins\"\n|- \n|2008||''[[American Dad]]''|| Old Woman #2||Episode: \"1600 Candles\"\n|-\n|2011||''[[Regular Show]]''|| Warden of the Internet||Episode: \"Go Viral\"\n|-\n|}\n{{div col|colwidth=26em}}\n* ''[[The Flintstone Comedy Show]]'' - Penny Pillar (1980)\n* ''[[The Flintstone Funnies]]'' - Penny Pillar, additional voices (1982-1984)\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Video games===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"white-space:nowrap\"\n|-\n!  Year !! Title !!Role!!Notes\n|- \n|2003||''[[Arc the Lad: Twilight of the Spirits]]''|| Geedo||\n|-\n|2005||''[[Tak: The Great Juju Challenge]]''|| Thunder Fist||\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2007||''[[Spider-Man 3 (video game)|Spider-Man 3]]''|| Additional voices||\n|-\n|''[[No More Heroes (video game)|No More Heroes]]''|| Speed Buster ||\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0564669|name=Mitzi McCall}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McCall, Mitzi}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American voice actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American women comedians]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Pittsburgh]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n|image =\n| name = Mitzi McCall\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1932|9|9}}  \n| birth_place = [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| occupation = Actress\n| years_active = 1955\u2013present\n| spouse = Jack Tolen (div.)<br>[[Charlie Brill]] (1960\u2013present)\n| children = Jenny Brill\n| signature = MitziMcCall.png\n| other_names = Mitzi Steiner\n}}\n'''Mitzi McCall''' (born September 9, 1932) is an American actress.\n\n==Life and career==\n\n=== Television ===\nIn the early 1950s, then known as '''Mitzi Steiner''', McCall had the ''Kiddie Castle'' program on [[KDKA-TV#DuMont origins (1949\u20131954)|WDTV-TV]] in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.<ref name=ppg/> She received national attention in 1952 via an Associated Press story about a five-year-old Pittsburgh girl with a cleft palate who spoke her first words while watching the actress in a pantomime on television. Afterward, doctors \"didn't know what to say. They held a special meeting, examined Claire, and told the happy parents that she was cured.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=TV, a Miracle of Science, Works 'Miracle Cure' on Girl |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23954903/mitzi_steiner/ |work=The Lincoln Star |agency=Associated Press |date=February 10, 1952 |location=Nebraska, Lincoln |page=7-D|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = September 22, 2018}} {{Open access}}</ref> In 1953, she was featured on ''Studio 10'', a program on [[KGTV#History|KFSD-TV]] in San Diego, California.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cohen |first1=Harold V. |title=The Drama Desk |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23966601/mitzi_steiner/ |work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette |date=November 10, 1953 |location=Pennsylvania, Pittsburgh |page=18|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = September 22, 2018}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n\nMcCall also performed in productions at the [[Pittsburgh Playhouse]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fanning |first1=Win |title=Radio and Television in Review |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23955286/mitzi_steiner/ |work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette |date=November 13, 1952 |location=Pennsylvania, Pittsburgh |page=35|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = September 22, 2018}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n\nShe was a performer on ''[[Rowan & Martin's Laugh-In]]''.{{r|etvs|page1=913}} McCall was also a series regular on television series such as ''[[Life Goes On (TV series)|Life Goes On]]'' and  ''[[Silk Stalkings]]'' (where she appeared as the wife of Brill's character),{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}} On animated series, she provided the voice of Auntie Marina in ''[[Snorks]]'',{{r|etvs|page1=986}} the voice of Mother Goose in ''[[Mother Goose and Grimm (TV series)|Mother Goose and Grimm]],''{{r|etvs|page1=718}} the voice of Sylvia Jenkins in ''[[Free for All (TV series)|Free for All]]'',{{r|etvs|page1=365}} and a variety of voices on ''The Paw Paws''.{{r|etvs|page1=819}} She played Miriam Lerner on ''[[Alright Already (TV series)|Alright Already]]''.<ref name=\"etvs\">{{cite book|last1=Terrace|first1=Vincent|title=Encyclopedia of Television Shows, 1925 through 2010|date=2011|publisher=McFarland & Company, Inc., Publishers|location=Jefferson, N.C.|isbn=978-0-7864-6477-7|page=33|edition=2nd}}</ref>\n\nOther credits include guest appearances on ''[[The Twilight Zone (1959 TV series)|The Twilight Zone]]'', ''[[Maude (TV series)|Maude]]'', ''[[Dharma & Greg]]'', ''[[Chuck (TV series)|Chuck]]'', as well as voice over work for many cartoons. In 1971, she was the voice of Penny on ''[[The Flintstones]]'' spin-off ''[[The Pebbles and Bamm-Bamm Show]]''.{{r|etvs|page1=820}} She was a panelist on the game show ''[[Match Game]]'' during its 1970s revival, and appeared with [[Charlie Brill]] on ''[[Tattletales]]''.\n\n=== McCall and Brill ===\nMcCall and Charlie Brill appeared on ''[[The Ed Sullivan Show]]'' on February 9, 1964, the episode that featured the U.S. television debut of [[The Beatles]]. Their act can be seen on the DVD of the Beatles' appearances on the Sullivan show.  They were interviewed in 2005 for the \"Big Break\" episode of [[Public Radio International|PRI]] radio program ''[[This American Life]],'' regarding their Beatles-Sullivan experience, including a dressing room encounter with [[John Lennon]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Human Spectacle 2015|url=http://www.thisamericanlife.org/radio-archives/episode/568/transcript|accessdate=October 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThey were spotted in 1963 while performing together in [[Honolulu]] by the Australian television producer John Collins, who produced ''[[The Tonight Show]]'' for TCN-9 in Sydney. Collins was seeking a replacement for the then unknown Irish comedian [[Dave Allen (comedian)|Dave Allen]], who had hosted the program for the previous two seasons and wanted to return to Ireland. Collins approached them and they agreed but could not start an Australian engagement until their Hawaiian engagement was complete. They recommended an American comedian, their friend [[Don Lane]], who was also working in Hawaii, to fill in during the meantime. Collins agreed to this. Lane started his Australian engagement and was an immediate success. Ratings were sensational and the network was delighted. It was going to be difficult if not impossible to replace him once the Brills became available. When they did, the preference was obvious and their engagement was cancelled after six weeks. Lane resumed their spot and remained successful in Australian television for the ensuing thirty-five years.\n\nIn 1967, McCall and Brill had a comedy recording, ''From Our Point of View'', released by [[ABC Records]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Special Merit Picks: Comedy |url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-Billboard-IDX/IDX/60s/1967/Billboard%201967-04-01-OCR-Page-0036.pdf#search=%22mitzi%20mccall%22 |accessdate=23 September 2018 |work=Billboard |date=April 1, 1967 |page=40}}</ref> Later that year, the duo signed with Congressional Records.<ref>{{cite news |title=Signings |url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-Billboard-IDX/IDX/60s/1967/Billboard%201967-11-04-OCR-Page-0020.pdf#search=%22mitzi%20mccall%22 |accessdate=23 September 2018 |work=Billboard |date=November 4, 1967 |page=20}}</ref>\n\n=== Shawlee and McCall ===\nIn the early 1960s, McCall and actress [[Joan Shawlee]] formed a team to perform as a night club act,<ref name=\"bg\">{{cite news |title=Joan Shawlee Sparkles Like a Spring Tonic |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23940101/joan_shawlee/ |work=The Boston Globe |date=April 30, 1961 |location=Massachusetts, Boston |page=65|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = September 21, 2018}} {{Open access}}</ref> debuting the act at the Club Robaire in Cleveland.<ref>{{cite news |title=They're Back |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23952672/joan_shawlee_mitzi_mccall/ |work=The Los Angeles Times |date=October 20, 1960 |location=California, Los Angeles |page=54|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = September 22, 2018}} {{Open access}}</ref> In January 1961, syndicated newspaper columnist [[Dorothy Kilgallen]] reported that the team was \"causing quite a stir\", and she cited the partners' discrepancy in height \u2014 \"Joan being six feet, three inches tall and Mitzi four feet, 10 inches short.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kilgallen |first1=Dorothy |title=The Voice of Broadway |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23952810/joan_shawlee_mitzi_mccall/ |work=The Mercury |date=January 7, 1961 |location=Pennsylvania, Pottstown |page=4|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = September 22, 2018}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, McCall had a supporting role as Bonnie in the film ''[[World's Greatest Dad]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nIn the early 1950s, McCall was married to Jack Tolen, a television director and production manager.<ref name=\"ppg\">{{cite news |last1=Fanning |first1=Win |title=Radio-Television |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/23954040/mitzi_mccall/ |work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette |date=June 29, 1954 |location=Pennsylvania, Pittsburgh |page=25|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = September 22, 2018}} {{Open access}}</ref> She and Charlie Brill met in 1959 and married the following year.<ref>California Marriage Index, 1960-1985.</ref> They have a daughter, L.A.-based yoga instructor Jenny Brill.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Films===\n{{div col|colwidth=26em}}\n* ''[[You're Never Too Young]]'' - Skeets Powell (1955)\n* ''[[Machine-Gun Kelly (film)|Machine-Gun Kelly]]'' - Harriet (uncredited) (1958)\n* ''[[War of the Satellites]]'' - Mitzi (1958)\n* ''[[The Cry Baby Killer]]'' - Evelyn (1958)\n* ''[[Deep Blood]]'' - Ben's Mother (1989)\n* ''[[White Palace (film)|White Palace]]'' - Sophie Rosen (1990)\n* ''[[The Opposite Sex and How to Live with Them]]'' - Freida Crown (1992)\n* ''[[EDtv]]'' - Fig Lady (1999)\n* ''Hard Four'' - Myrna Segal (2007)\n* ''[[World's Greatest Dad]]'' - Bonnie (2009)\n* ''[[Crimson Peak]]'' - Additional voices (2015)\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Television series===\n{{div col|colwidth=26em}}\n* ''[[Rowan & Martin's Laugh-In]]'' - \"herself\" in \"The Fun Couple\" sketches (1968-1969)\n* ''[[Maude (TV series)|Maude]]'' - Estelle Ellinger (Episode: \"Nostalgia Party\") (1974)\n* ''[[Family (1976 TV series)|Family]]'' - Sally (Episode: \"Princess in the Tower\") (1978)\n* ''[[Life Goes On (TV series)|Life Goes On]]'' - Midge (1991-1992)\n* ''[[Silk Stalkings]]'' - Fran Lipschitz (1993-1999)\n* ''[[Seinfeld]]'' - Donna (Episode: \"The Secretary\") (1994)\n* ''[[Ellen (TV series)|Ellen]]'' - Rochelle Shapiro (Episode: \"Too Hip for the Room\") (1996)\n* ''[[Alright Already (TV series)|Alright Already]]'' - Miriam Lerner (1997-1998)\n* ''[[Caroline in the City]]'' - Lois (Episode: \"Caroline and the Little White Lies\") (1998)\n* ''[[Becker]]'' - Mrs. Gould (Episode: \"Hate Thy Neighbor\") (1999)\n* ''[[Dharma & Greg]]'' - Florence (Episode: \"With a Little Help from My Friend\") (2001)\n* ''[[The Suite Life of Zack and Cody]]'' - Doreen (Episode \"Club Twin\") (2007)\n* ''[[Hannah Montana]]'' - Woman (Episode: \"My Best Friend's Boyfriend\") (2007)\n* ''[[Chuck (TV series)|Chuck]]'' - Blanche (Episode: \"Chuck Versus the Broken Heart\") (2009)\n{{div col end}}\n\n====Animation====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"white-space:nowrap\"\n|-\n!  Year !! Title !!Role!!Notes\n|- \n|1971||''[[The Pebbles and Bamm-Bamm Show]]''|| Penny Pillar||16 Episodes\n|- \n|1972-1974||''[[The Flintstones Comedy Hour]]''|| Penny Pillar||13 Episodes\n|- \n|1977-1978||''[[Fred Flintstone and Friends]]''|| Penny Pillar||\n|- \n|1980-1981||''[[Th