{"title_page": "Ratna Omidvar", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox CanadianSenator\n| name             = Ratna Omidvar\n| image            = Senator Ratna Omidvar.png\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n| honorific-suffix = {{post-nominals|size=100%|CM|OOnt}}\n| office           = [[Senate of Canada|Senator]] from [[Ontario]]\n| term_start       = March 18, 2016\n| term_end         =\n| nominator        = [[Justin Trudeau]]\n| appointer        = [[David Johnston]]\n| party            = [[Independent Senators Group]]\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1949|11|5}}\n| birth_place      = [[Punjab, India|Punjab]], [[India]]\n| occupation       = Executive director, professor\n| spouse           = \n|}}\n'''Ratna Omidvar''' {{post-nominals|CM|OOnt}} (born November 5, 1949) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] politician and academic, who was named to the [[Senate of Canada]] to represent [[Ontario]] on March 18, 2016.<ref name=\":0\">[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/trudeau-set-to-appoint-seven-new-senators/article29285218/ \"Trudeau to appoint seven new senators\"]. ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', March 18, 2016.</ref>\n\n== Early life and academic career ==\nOriginally from [[Amritsar]], [[India]], she was educated at the [[University of Delhi]].<ref name=fighter>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/careers/careers-leadership/gdx-executive-director-a-fighter-for-immigration-inclusion-and-diversity/article24013798/ \"A fighter for immigration, inclusion and diversity\"]. ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', April 17, 2015.</ref> Later moving to Canada, she became executive director of the Maytree Foundation, a charitable organization to combat [[poverty]] in Canada, before departing in 2014 to found the Global Diversity Exchange at the Ted Rogers School of Management, [[Ryerson University]]<ref name=fighter /> where she was a distinguished visiting professor.\n\nOmidvar is the current co-chair of the Global Future Council on Migration hosted by the [[World Economic Forum]]. She is also a director at the [[Environics|Environics Institute]], and [[Samara (charitable organisation)|Samara Canada]]. She is the Toronto Region Immigrant Employment Council\u2019s chair emerita and was formerly the chair of Lifeline Syria.\n\nOmidvar is co-author of ''Flight and Freedom: Stories of Escape to Canada'' (2015), an Open Book Toronto best book of 2015 and one of the Toronto Star's top five good reads from [[The Word on the Street (literary festival)|Word on the Street]]. She is also a contributor to ''The Harper Factor'' (2016) and co-editor of ''Five Good Ideas: Practical Strategies for Non-Profit Success'' (2011).\n\n== Senator ==\nOmidvar was named to the [[Senate of Canada]] by Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]] to represent Ontario on March 18, 2016, joining the [[Independent Senators Group]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn October 2018, Omidvar introduced a motion to strip [[Aung San Suu Kyi]] of her [[honorary Canadian citizenship]] over her government's actions in the [[Rohingya conflict]]. Passed unanimously, the measure stripped Suu Kyi of the honour, since the House of Commons had passed a similar measure earlier in the month.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/politics/article-senate-votes-unanimously-to-strip-aung-san-suu-kyis-honorary-canadian/|title=Senate votes unanimously to strip Aung San Suu Kyi\u2019s honorary Canadian citizenship|last=Curry|first=Bill|date=October 2, 2018|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|access-date=October 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOmidvar notably interacted with Laird Hunter on October 22, 2018, in a Senate Committee dealing with charities and non-profits.\n\n== Honours ==\nOmidvar was appointed to the [[Order of Ontario]] in 2005 and became a [[Member of the Order of Canada]] in 2011,<ref name=cbc>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/ratna-omidvar-independent-senator-1.3498050 \"Ratna Omidvar, Toronto expert on diversity, to sit as independent senator\"]. [[CBC News]], March 18, 2016.</ref> with both honours recognizing her advocacy work on behalf of immigrants and devotion to reducing inequality in Canada. She also received an honorary doctorate in laws [[York University]] in 2012. In 2014, Omidvar received the Cross of the [[Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]] in recognition of her contribution to the advancement of German-Canadian relations.\n\nOmidvar has also been recognized by Canada's national newspaper, ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', by being named as its Nation Builder of the Decade for Citizenship in 2010. In 2016, [[CivicAction]] awarded her with their Lifetime Achievement Award for Civic Leadership in the [[Greater Toronto Area]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sDBNY6dmUTQ A leadership journey through flight and compassion | Ratna Omidvar | TEDxBerlinSalon]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yQskdD1cnaA Ratna Omidvar on Migration | World Economic Forum]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC6Ccs4xSIgKkvhh2iXYVizw Ratna Omidvar Youtube channel]\n*{{CanParlbio|ID=18639}}\n*[http://www.ratnaomidvar.ca Ratna Omidvar Homepage]\n\n{{Senate of Canada}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Omidvar, Ratna}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Canadian senators from Ontario]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Senate of Canada]]\n[[Category:Independent Canadian senators]]\n[[Category:Indian emigrants to Canada]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of Canada]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of Ontario]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Cross of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Amritsar]]\n[[Category:Ryerson University faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Delhi alumni]]\n[[Category:Independent Senators Group]]\n[[Category:Women in Ontario politics]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian women politicians]]\n[[Category:Canadian politicians of Indian descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox CanadianSenator\n| name             = Ratna Omidvar\n| image            = Senator Ratna Omidvar.png\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n| honorific-suffix = {{post-nominals|size=100%|CM|OOnt}}\n| office           = [[Senate of Canada|Senator]] from [[Ontario]]\n| term_start       = March 18, 2016\n| term_end         =\n| nominator        = [[Justin Trudeau]]\n| appointer        = [[David Johnston]]\n| party            = [[Independent Senators Group]]\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1949|11|5}}\n| birth_place      = [[Punjab, India|Punjab]], [[India]]\n| occupation       = Executive director, professor\n| spouse           = \n|}}\n'''Ratna Omidvar''' {{post-nominals|CM|OOnt}} (born November 5, 1949) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] politician and academic, who was named to the [[Senate of Canada]] to represent [[Ontario]] on March 18, 2016.<ref name=\":0\">[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/trudeau-set-to-appoint-seven-new-senators/article29285218/ \"Trudeau to appoint seven new senators\"]. ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', March 18, 2016.</ref>\n\n== Early life and academic career ==\nOriginally from [[Amritsar]], [[India]], she was educated at the [[University of Delhi]].<ref name=fighter>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/careers/careers-leadership/gdx-executive-director-a-fighter-for-immigration-inclusion-and-diversity/article24013798/ \"A fighter for immigration, inclusion and diversity\"]. ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', April 17, 2015.</ref> Later moving to Canada, she became executive director of the Maytree Foundation, a charitable organization to combat [[poverty]] in Canada, before departing in 2014 to found the Global Diversity Exchange at the Ted Rogers School of Management, [[Ryerson University]]<ref name=fighter /> where she is currently a distinguished visiting professor.\n\nOmidvar is the current co-chair of the Global Future Council on Migration hosted by the [[World Economic Forum]]. She is also a director at the [[Environics|Environics Institute]], and [[Samara (charitable organisation)|Samara Canada]]. She is the Toronto Region Immigrant Employment Council\u2019s chair emerita and was formerly the chair of Lifeline Syria.\n\nOmidvar is co-author of ''Flight and Freedom: Stories of Escape to Canada'' (2015), an Open Book Toronto best book of 2015 and one of the Toronto Star's top five good reads from [[The Word on the Street (literary festival)|Word on the Street]]. She is also a contributor to ''The Harper Factor'' (2016) and co-editor of ''Five Good Ideas: Practical Strategies for Non-Profit Success'' (2011).\n\n== Senator ==\nOmidvar was named to the [[Senate of Canada]] by Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]] to represent Ontario on March 18, 2016, joining the [[Independent Senators Group]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn October 2018, Omidvar introduced a motion to strip [[Aung San Suu Kyi]] of her [[honorary Canadian citizenship]] over her government's actions in the [[Rohingya conflict]]. Passed unanimously, the measure stripped Suu Kyi of the honour, since the House of Commons had passed a similar measure earlier in the month.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/politics/article-senate-votes-unanimously-to-strip-aung-san-suu-kyis-honorary-canadian/|title=Senate votes unanimously to strip Aung San Suu Kyi\u2019s honorary Canadian citizenship|last=Curry|first=Bill|date=October 2, 2018|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|access-date=October 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOmidvar notably interacted with Laird Hunter on October 22, 2018, in a Senate Committee dealing with charities and non-profits.\n\n== Honours ==\nOmidvar was appointed to the [[Order of Ontario]] in 2005 and became a [[Member of the Order of Canada]] in 2011,<ref name=cbc>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/ratna-omidvar-independent-senator-1.3498050 \"Ratna Omidvar, Toronto expert on diversity, to sit as independent senator\"]. [[CBC News]], March 18, 2016.</ref> with both honours recognizing her advocacy work on behalf of immigrants and devotion to reducing inequality in Canada. She also received an honorary doctorate in laws [[York University]] in 2012. In 2014, Omidvar received the Cross of the [[Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]] in recognition of her contribution to the advancement of German-Canadian relations.\n\nOmidvar has also been recognized by Canada's national newspaper, ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', by being named as its Nation Builder of the Decade for Citizenship in 2010. In 2016, [[CivicAction]] awarded her with their Lifetime Achievement Award for Civic Leadership in the [[Greater Toronto Area]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sDBNY6dmUTQ A leadership journey through flight and compassion | Ratna Omidvar | TEDxBerlinSalon]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yQskdD1cnaA Ratna Omidvar on Migration | World Economic Forum]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC6Ccs4xSIgKkvhh2iXYVizw Ratna Omidvar Youtube channel]\n*{{CanParlbio|ID=18639}}\n*[http://www.ratnaomidvar.ca Ratna Omidvar Homepage]\n\n{{Senate of Canada}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Omidvar, Ratna}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Canadian senators from Ontario]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Senate of Canada]]\n[[Category:Independent Canadian senators]]\n[[Category:Indian emigrants to Canada]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of Canada]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of Ontario]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Cross of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Amritsar]]\n[[Category:Ryerson University faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Delhi alumni]]\n[[Category:Independent Senators Group]]\n[[Category:Women in Ontario politics]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian women politicians]]\n[[Category:Canadian politicians of Indian descent]]\n", "name_user": "BadNewsBear", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ratna_Omidvar"}
